l economy of the Gulf that ties together a variety of issues usually treated separately: Kuwait's National Assembly, Dubai's real estate boom, the paucity of citizen labor in the private sector, class divisions among citizens, the caste divide between citizens and noncitizens, and the politics of land.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocratizationzKuwait. 0aDemocratizationzUnited Arab Emirates. 0aEconomic developmentxPolitical aspectszKuwait. 0aEconomic developmentxPolitical aspectszUnited Arab Emirates. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexPolitical aspectszKuwait. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexPolitical aspectszUnited Arab Emirates. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aMiddle East Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aglobal business centers, dubai political economy, kuwait political economy, gulf monarchies, kuwait parliament, oil economy, political liberalization, dubai real estate, kuwait national assembly.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145469140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801454691423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801454691/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles